postcontent: An excellent condition Springfield M1A. This was listed with the Sadlak steel scope mount shown in the photos but people haven't been interested in the mount. The factory shipping tag is dated 1-29-98. I haven't found anything that shows Springfield's catalog number. The rifle is built with desirable original new GI parts from Harrington & Richardson. None of the marked parts are Springfield Armory reproductions. The op-rod, bolt, and trigger assembly are HR marked. The barrel is by TRW, dated 6-63.It has a GI contract rear sight with a correct M-meter elevation knob.The front sight is a standard 0.072" width blade, tapered towards the front. The rifle has a California-legal muzzle brake. It screws on and is readily replaced with a flash hider if you live in a free state where flash hiders are not demonized.The stock is GI, walnut, and remains about new condition. There's few marks and no cracks or chips or major problems. The edges are still pretty sharp, not beat up. It appears that the left side forward of the grip was sanded, as the wood is slightly lighter colored there. The acceptance stamp is still visible though on the left side beneath the rear corner of the receiver. The grip shows two circle-P proof marks and thus I suspect the sanding to the left side was done during the rebuild and that this stock was removed from a rifle that was rebuilt and later destroyed, unused. The buttplate looks good, not scarred or ugly, with nice original finish.The bore is clean, shiny throughout, and looks as-new. No copper, dark spots, or defects visible. The finish at the bottom where the op rod often touches is still there, suggesting the rifle hasn't seen a lot of use.The finish on the hammer and op rod tab and cam areas shows little wear.

It's essentially a bore chambering feature that snugs up on the 223 round a bit, while still allowing the 5.56 to fit as well. Is rumored to offer up improved accuracy. You be the judge.The rifle is very well made, tight, no gaps between upper and lower, and will make someone a sweet shooter. I picked it up the Tanner show last weekend, and have changed my mind on what my needs are for a defensive weapon. My asking price is a great deal given the rifle's new condition and the added sights (the OR model does not come with sights) - I'm' essentially throwing in the sights for free. Due to Colorado's laws, guns sales between private parties still requires a background check, so we'll have to meet at a gun store that can facilitate the required paperwork. I have one in mind that will charge the buyer $16 for the check, but you'll pay no tax on the deal since it's between private parties.Let me know if you have any questions, and thanks for looking!

title: For Sale:  Winchester Model 12, 28 Gauge
postcontent:
Winchester Model 12, 28 Gauge
Extremely rare Winchester Model 12, 28 gauge in good condition, 70-80%.  All original, solid rib barrel, full choke, matching serial numbers.   It has a few light scratches on the right side of the receiver and a few nicks in the stock.  Approximately 2,600 of the Model 12-28 were produced, and only a few hundred has the solid rib.  Bore has a mirror finish.  Checkered pistol grip and forend. 
  The Model 12 Winchester was produced continuously from 1912-1980. Over 2,027,500 were produced both in standard and deluxe (Pigeon) grades. Pigeon grades were first listed in 1914 and disc. during the war (1941). Reintroduced in 1948, they were disc. permanently in 1964, after which the Super Pigeon Grade became available only on a custom-order basis from Winchester's Custom Gun Shop. These guns are worth 50%-300% premiums depending on gauge, barrel lengths, stock options, engraving patterns, etc. With an attrition rate of approximately 33%, Model 12s with rare features produced 50 years ago will only be much rarer today (and expensive). 28 ga. guns were built between 1937 and 1960. Gauge rarity in increasing order is 12 ga. (approx. 360,000 mfg. 1925-1943), 16 ga. (approx. 190,000 mfg. 1925-1943), 20 ga. (approx. 71,000 mfg. 1925-1943), .410 bore (Model 42), and 28 ga. (approx. 2,600 mfg. 1937-1943). Serialization breakdown by year of manufacture is provided under the "Serialization" section of this book. When collecting Model 12s, ser. nos. on the underside of receiver (forward end), should match ser. no. on bottom rear of Mag. tube.Serious inquiries only.  Sorry, no trades.  All FFL rules and regs apply.  Buyer pays shipping or sales tax.

title: For Sale:  1924 Colt "Transition" 1911
location: Myrtle Beach, Myrtle Beach, South Carolina
postcontent: This is a collectors dream, there were only 14,999 of these guns produced, and 10,000 were strickly military.  Serial numbers can be matched in colt books as being a 1924.  This is one of the 4999 produced and sold to civilians.  It is know as a "Transition" bc from 1924 to 1938 the US military didn't have a contract in place for the 1911 to be supplied and carried by the military.  In 1938 this gun become the US Army 1911.  It is in all original condition minus the firing pin has been upgraded to a stainless pin.  It functions and looks incredible for its age.  Just google the 1924 Colt Transition and you may find 3 or 4 for sale and range in price from 5,570 - 10,000.  Unfortunatly I need to see this gun, and have it priced not only to sell, but to leave you some room for profit on your end.  Please feel free and ask and questions you might have.
